 as triumph. He uncovers how, dealing with loss and destruction on an unimaginable scale, Soviet readers and writers embraced the story of martyred Stalingrad, embedding it into the Russian psyche for decades to come.Featuring lost work by Vasily Grossman alongside texts by luminaries such as Konstantin Simonov, Viktor Nekrasov, and Ilya Ehrenburg, Stalingrad Lives offers a literary perspective on the Soviet Union at war.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aStalingrad, Battle of, Volgograd, Russia, 1942-1943vPersonal narratives, Soviet. 0aStalingrad, Battle of, Volgograd, Russia, 1942-1943xPropaganda. 0aStalingrad, Battle of, Volgograd, Russia, 1942-1943, in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aAdolph Hitler.  aAleksandr Shcherbakov.  aAlexander.  aBattle.  aCivilians.  aCorrespondents.  aDavid Ortenberg.  aEastern Front.  aFiction.  aHermann Göring.  aJosef.  aJoseph Stalin.  aKonstantin Simonov.  aKrasnaya Zvezda.  aNewspapers.  aOperation Blue.  aPapers.  aPravda.  aPropaganda.  aRed Star.  aRussian Literature.  aSecond World War.  aSocialist Realism.  aSoviet Union.  aSovinformbyuro.  aStalingrad.  aStories.  aStreet Fighting.  aSubjectivity.  aTales.  aTranslation.  aTrauma.  aUSSR.  aVasilii.  aVasily Grossman.  aViktor Nekrasov.  aVolgograd.  aWarfare.  aWorld War II.  aaccounts.  abelief.  afrontline.  amemoirs.  amemory.  amilitary history.  amyth.  arealist.  aresurrection.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228015161?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228015161423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228015161/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles